Longest Communication Chain in an Organization (Tree Diameter)

A company has a hierarchical organizational structure where each employee may have up to two direct subordinates. This structure forms a binary tree, where:



Each node represents an employee

A connection (edge) represents a direct reporting relationship
Information can flow between employees through these reporting links.


The efficiency of communication is defined as the maximum number of connections (edges) required to pass information between any two employees in the organization.



Your task is to compute this maximum value.

In simpler terms, find the diameter of the binary tree — the longest path between any two nodes (measured in number of edges).

Input format :
First line: Integer n → number of employees
Second line: Space-separated values representing the hierarchy in level-order
Use -1 to represent no employee (missing node
Output format :
Print a single integer → maximum number of connections between any two employees
Code constraints :
1 ≤ n ≤ 10^4
-100 ≤ value ≤ 100
Hierarchy is valid (no cycles)
Structure may not be complete
Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
3
1 2 3
Output 1 :
2
Input 2 :
7
1 2 3 4 -1 -1 5
Output 2 :
4



Solution:

#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class Node{
    public:
    int data;
    Node* left;
    Node* right;
    
    Node(int val){
        data = val;
        
        left = right = nullptr;
    }
};

Node* root = nullptr;

void insert(int val){
    
    Node* nn = new Node(val);
    
    if(root == nullptr){
        root = nn;
        return ;
    }
    
    Node* temp = root;
    
    while(true){
        
        
        if(temp->data < val){
            if(temp -> right == nullptr){
                temp->right = nn;
                return ;
            }
            temp = temp->right;
        }
        else
        {
            if(temp->left == nullptr)
            {
                temp->left = nn;
                return ;
            }
            
            temp = temp->left;
            
        }
        
    }
    
    return ;
    
}

int diameter = 0;

int print(Node* temp){
    
    if(temp == nullptr){
        return 0;
    }
    
   int l = print(temp->left);
   int r = print(temp->right);
   
    diameter = max(diameter,l+r);
   
   
    
    return 1 + max(l,r);
}

int main(){
    
    int n;
    cin>>n;
    
    vector<int>arr(n);
    
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        cin>>arr[i];
        insert(arr[i]);
    }
    
  
    
    print(root);
    cout<<diameter;
    
    
    
}
